safe	1
with	1
her;	1
but	1
when	1
there	1
was	1
a	1
chance	1
of	1
a	1
husband	1
coming	1
forward,	1
who	1
would	1
ask	1
for	1
all	1
that	1
the	1
law	1
would	1
give	1
him,	1
then	1
her	1
father	1
thought	1
it	1
time	1
to	1
put	1
a	1
stop	1
on	1
it.	1
He	1
wanted	1
her	1
to	1
sign	1
a	1
paper,	1
so	1
that	1
whether	1
she	1
married	1
or	1
not,	1
he	1
could	1
use	1
her	1
money.	1
When	1
she	1
wouldn't	1
do	1
it,	1
he	1
kept	1
on	1
worrying	1
her	1
until	1
she	1
got	1
brain-fever,	1
and	1
for	1
six	1
weeks	1
was	1
at	1
death's	1
door.	1
Then	1
she	1
got	1
better	1
at	1
last,	1
all	1
worn	1
to	1
a	1
shadow,	1
and	1
with	1
her	1
beautiful	1
hair	1
cut	1
off;	1
but	1
that	1
didn't	1
make	1
no	1
change	1
in	1
her	1
young	1
man,	1
and	1
he	1
stuck	1
to	1
her	1
as	1
true	1
as	1
man	1
could	1
be."	1
	1
"Ah,"	1
said	1
Holmes,	1
"I	1
think	1
that	1
what	1
you	1
have	1
been	1
good	1
enough	1
to	1
tell	1
us	1
makes	1
the	1
matter	1
fairly	1
clear,	1
and	1
that	1
I	1
can	1
deduce	1
all	1
that	1
remains.	1
Mr.	1
Rucastle	1
then,	1
I	1
presume,	1
took	1
to	1
this	1
system	1
of	1
imprisonment?"	1
	1
"Yes,	1
sir."	1
	1
"And	1
brought	1
Miss	1
Hunter	1
down	1
from	1
London	1
in	1
order	1
to	1
get	1
rid	1
of	1
the	1
disagreeable	1
persistence	1
of	1
Mr.	1
Fowler."	1
	1
"That	1
was	1
it,	1
sir."	1
	1
"But	1
Mr.	1
Fowler	1
being	1
a	1
persevering	1
man,	1
as	1
a	1
good	1
seaman	1
should	1
be,	1
blockaded	1
the	1
house,	1
and	1
having	1
met	1
you	1
succeeded	1
by	1
certain	1
arguments,	1
metallic	1
or	1
otherwise,	1
in	1
convincing	1
you	1
that	1
your	1
interests	1
were	1
the	1
same	1
as	1
his."	1
	1
"Mr.	1
Fowler	1
was	1
a	1
very	1
kind-spoken,	1
free-handed	1
gentleman,"	1
said	1
Mrs.	1
Toller	1
serenely.	1
	1
"And	1
in	1
this	1
way	1
he	1
managed	1
that	1
your	1
good	1
man	1
should	1
have	1
no	1
want	1
of	1
drink,	1
and	1
that	1
a	1
ladder	1
should	1
be	1
ready	1
at	1
the	1
moment	1
when	1
your	1
master	1
had	1
gone	1
out."	1
	1
"You	1
have	1
it,	1
sir,	1
just	1
as	1
it	1
happened."	1
	1
"I	1
am	1
sure	1
we	1
owe	1
you	1
an	1
